'''''Shugenja''''' (修験者) are practitioners of the [[Religions of Japan|Japanese]] [[religion]] of [[Shugendō]]. They are sometimes known as ''[[yamabushi]]''.

==Role-playing games==
===Bushido===
In ''[[Bushido (role-playing game)|Bushido]]'', a [[role-playing game]] published in 1981 by [[Fantasy Games Unlimited]], Shugenja are portrayed as [[Wizard (fantasy)|wizards]].

===Legend of the Five Rings===
In the ''[[Legend of the Five Rings]]'' [[collectible card game]], ''shugenja'' are [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]]-users, similar to wizards. Their spells are given power by the five different varieties of [[kami]] that can be found in [[Rokugan]]. Their magic is referred to as Elemental Magic, as opposed to Bloodspeakers who use Blood Magic. In the [[Legend of the Five Rings Role-Playing Game|role-playing game]], being a ''shugenja'' is one of the main alternatives in character creation.

===Dungeons & Dragons===
The [[Shugenja (Dungeons & Dragons)#Advanced Dungeons & Dragons|shugenja]] (with the alternate spelling ''shukenja'') was introduced in the original [[Editions of Dungeons & Dragons#Advanced Dungeons & Dragons|first edition]] ''[[Oriental Adventures]]'' book as a subclass of cleric.<ref>[[Gary Gygax|Gygax, Gary]], with [[David Cook (game designer)|David Cook]], and [[François Marcela-Froideval]]. ''Oriental Adventures'' ([[TSR, Inc.|TSR]], 1985)</ref> A version of this class (also called [[Shugenja (Dungeons & Dragons)|shugenja]]) was incorporated into ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'' in the [[Editions of Dungeons & Dragons#Dungeons & Dragons 3rd edition|third edition]]  ''[[Oriental Adventures]]'' [[sourcebook]], and revised in the [[Editions of Dungeons & Dragons#Dungeons & Dragons v3.5|3.5 edition]] sourcebook ''[[Complete Divine]]''.

