[[ja:修験者]]

'''Strixology''' is a genre of writing about the reality and dangers of [[witch]]es, their origins, character and power; often in the context of [[theology]] or of [[demonology]].{{sfnb|Pavlac|2009|p= 205}} (The Latin word ''strix'' can mean "screech-owl" or "witch".<ref>
[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/strix See "strix" in Wiktionary.]
</ref>)

During the [[early modern period]] strixologists refuted the reality of witches and contributed to the decline of [[witch-hunts]].{{sfnb|Pavlac|2009|p=vii}}

As a systematic study, strixology emerged during the period 1431—1439 at the [[Council of Basel]] - an ecclesiastical council where [[theologians]] and [[demonologist]]s met and debated what was seen as the [[Devil]]'s work, [[Magic (supernatural)|magic]]al observations and confessions of witches.{{sfnb|Pavlac|2009|pp=53-54}} Those issues were not a primary purpose of the Council. Nonetheless, the subject of one of the discussions was a peasant named [[Stedelen]] who was believed to have committed ''[[maleficia]]''{{efn|harmful acts of witchcraft}} and who said under torture that he was a part of a secret society of Devil-worshippers. This story was disturbing enough to be reported to the council by Peter of Simmental and described in great detail.{{sfnb|Pavlac|2009|p=54}}

This case and similar revelations were later used by the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] professor [[Johannes Nider]], a participant at the Council's meetings, as examples in his ''[[Formicarius]]'' (1436-1438) a book that laid the foundations of strixology. Scholars cited this significant work for centuries.{{sfnb|Pavlac|2009|pp=54-55}} Around the time ''Formicarius'' was published, there was a relatively small number of witch-hunt victims - estimated to have been in the hundreds.{{sfnb|Pavlac|2009|p=56}} This changed at the end of the 15th century, partially due to the publication of the infamous ''[[Malleus Maleficarum]]'' which cemented belief in the reality of witches{{sfnb|Pavlac|2009|p= 56}} and in the higher susceptibility of women to take part in witchcraft.{{sfnb|Pavlac|2009|p= 57}} The book proclaimed that “evils which are performed by witches exceed all other sin which God has ever permitted to be done.…”.{{sfnb|Summers|1971|loc=[Part
I., Q. 14], 74}}

